The ideality factor can be determined experimentally by measuring the current–voltage characteristics of the DSSC and fitting the data to the equation57,58:6I=I0expqVNkT-1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$I = I_{0} {\text{exp}}\left( {\frac{qV}{{NkT}} - 1} \right)$$\end{document}where I is the current, I0 is the saturation current, q is the elementary charge, V is the voltage, N is the ideality factor, k is the Boltzmann constant, and T is the temperature. The ideality factor can be obtained from the slope of the plot of Ln(I) vs V, and it quantifies how many charge carriers recombine during this procedure. In other words, the ideality factor quantifies the level of charge carrier recombination and, consequently, related to determining how efficiently a DSSC transforms sunlight into energy. In our intended design, the ideality factor was 1.32.

Consequently, low Rsh causes a loss in photovoltage and may also have a slight effect on the collected photocurrent. In this investigation, we have varied the series and shunt resistance from 1 to 5 Ωcm2 and 100–600 Ωcm2 to observe the influence on device performance and output parameters. Under ideal illumination, the typical J–V characteristic of a photovoltaic cell may be characterized using the Shockley equation.7JSC=J0expeV-JRSNkT-1+V-JRSRSH-JPh\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$J_{SC} = J_{0} \left[ {exp\left( {\frac{{e\left( {V - JR_{S} } \right)}}{NkT}} \right) - 1} \right] + \frac{{V - JR_{S} }}{{R_{SH} }} - J_{Ph}$$\end{document}where JPh denotes photocurrent density, J0 denotes dark saturation current, T is room temperature, and e denotes charge on an electron. In ideal conditions, Rs would be 0, and Rsh would be limitless.

One of the necessary factors in enhancing the productivity and outcomes of DSSCs is charge carrier mobility. The average mobility of charge carriers describes how easily charge carriers are moving from one place to another without trapping, described by a relation.8μen=μeonfreenfree+ntrap\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mu_{e} \left( n \right) = \frac{{\mu_{e}^{o} n_{free} }}{{n_{free} + n_{trap} }}$$\end{document}
